**Every Page — Full UX, Content, Input, Output, Dynamic Behavior**

---

**PAGE 1 — AUTH**
Routes: `/login` `/signup` -+-

Three routes, one visual shell. The layout never changes — centered card on a white background, logo top, form in the middle.

Inputs: email, password, Google OAuth trigger, magic link trigger. On signup, also: name.

Outputs: JWT access token + refresh token stored in Supabase session. On success, redirects to `/onboarding` if first login, `/` if returning user.

States the page has to handle: loading after form submit, Google OAuth redirect in progress, invalid credentials error, email not verified state, invite token expired, invite token already accepted, rate limited after too many attempts.

Every error is specific. "Wrong password" is not "something went wrong." "This invite expired 3 days ago" is not "invalid link."

---

**PAGE 2 — home**
Route: `/`

Seven steps. Linear. Cannot be skipped except step 6 and step 7. The page reads from the database on load to know which step the user last completed — if they close the browser and come back, they resume where they left off.

Step 1 reads nothing from the database. It writes: user email + hashed password to Supabase Auth.

Step 2 reads nothing. It writes: org name, industry, size to the organisations table. Also creates the org_members record linking this user as owner.

Step 3 reads: list of providers (Gemini, Claude, OpenAI) from a static config. Writes: encrypted API key to the api_keys table after a live validation call to the provider. If the key fails validation, it tells the user exactly why — 401 means invalid key, 429 means quota exhausted, timeout means network issue.

Step 4 reads: nothing. Writes: first project record to the projects table with status CREATED.

Step 5 reads: the project just created. Writes: JD text to the project. Triggers the JD Audit job in the background. Shows a live status indicator — the audit is running while the user reads the result preview on the right.

Step 6 reads: the JD audit output just generated. Displays it. No user input. The user sees what the system produced from their JD — must-haves extracted, seniority inferred, quality score, ghost candidate card. This is the first moment of value.

Step 7 reads: the project. Accepts file uploads. Writes: resume files to Supabase Storage, candidate records to the candidates table, queues analysis jobs. Can be skipped — redirects to dashboard either way.

On completion: redirects to `/project/:id` for the project just created, not to the dashboard. The recruiter goes straight into their first result.

