**PAGE 3 — DASHBOARD**
Route: `/dashboard`

The results hub. Reads everything, writes nothing directly.

On load it queries: all projects belonging to this org, ordered by updated_at descending. For each project it reads: project name, role, status, candidate count, top candidate name and score, qualification rate, average inflation rate, hidden gems count, pool health score.

This is not one query. It is either multiple joined queries or a materialized view depending on performance needs. The frontend receives one API response per page load — not one per project card.

What the page shows:

Top: global org stats — total candidates analyzed across all time, average qualification rate across all projects, active API key status, total projects.

Main body: project result cards in a grid. Each card is a complete summary of one project's intelligence output. Not a navigation element — an information element that happens to be clickable.

Each project card dynamically shows one of four states. State one: CREATED — project exists, no JD uploaded yet. The card shows the role name and a prompt to add a JD. State two: ANALYZING — candidates are being processed. The card shows a live progress indicator — X of Y complete — updated via Supabase Realtime without page refresh. State three: COMPLETE — full results visible on the card directly. Score, qualification rate, inflation rate, top candidate, hidden gems count. State four: FAILED — something broke. The card shows which step failed and a retry option.

The recruiter never has to click into a project to know if it's worth clicking into. The card tells them.

Filters across the top: All, Active, Complete, Archived. These filter the project grid client-side — no new API call.

Sort options: Most recent, Highest pool score, Most candidates, Role name alphabetical.

Search: live text filter across project names and role titles. Client-side. Instant.

New project button: top right corner. Opens a modal — project name, role, department, seniority, API key selection. On submit creates the project record and redirects to `/project/:id`.

The dashboard has no empty state problem after the first project completes. Before the first project, it shows a single centered prompt with a button to create the first project.

Dynamic behavior: any project currently in ANALYZING state updates its progress bar in real time via Supabase Realtime subscription. The recruiter can have the dashboard open while analysis runs elsewhere and watch the card update without touching the browser.

