**PAGE 5 — CANDIDATE DETAIL**
Route: `/dashboard/project/:id/candidate/:cid`

One candidate. Full intelligence output. Everything the system knows about this person on one screen.

On load: reads the candidate record, all analysis output blobs, the project's ghost candidate profile, the JD audit output. Single API call returns all of this.

Header: candidate name, current title, final score large in JetBrains Mono, rank out of total, trajectory badge, ghost match score, insider signal score.

Left column, 65% width:

Score breakdown — five bars, one per dimension, animated fill on load. Each bar has a label, a score, and a one-line explanation of what drove that score. Not just numbers — the system explains its reasoning for each dimension.

Red flags section — only visible if flags exist. Each flag in plain English. The type of flag, the evidence from the resume, the severity. Not jargon. A recruiter who has never heard of "achievement echo absence" understands what it means when it says "Claims to have led a major ML platform launch in 2022 but received no promotion, title change, or company advancement in the 18 months following."

System narrative — one to three paragraphs. What the resume claims versus what the system actually found. This is the most human-readable output on the page. It reads like a senior recruiter's assessment, because the prompt that generates it asks for exactly that.

Right column, 35% width:

Interrogation Engine — three question cards. Dark navy background, terminal style. Each question shows: the question text, the claim it is probing, what a strong answer looks like, what a weak answer signals. The recruiter walks into the interview with this panel open on their phone.

Ghost Gap Report — what this candidate is missing compared to the ideal. Each gap has a severity label and a specific description. Not "needs more experience" — "No evidence of production incident handling or post-mortem authorship despite 4 years in senior engineering roles."

Insider Signal grid — two columns. Present signals with blue checkmarks. Absent signals with red x marks. Pride flags listed separately with the specific claim and why it's a flag for the seniority level claimed.

Back button returns to the project workspace with scroll position preserved — the recruiter lands back exactly where they were in the candidate list.
 
